Pedagogue -- tParainesis as an Ancient Genre-Designation. The Case of the ‘Euthalian Apparatus’ and the ‘Affiliated Argumenta’ -- tWisdom, Paraenesis and the Roots of Monasticism -- tBibliography -- tSelect Index of Ancient Literature -- tIndex of Personal Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn up-to-date discussion of early Christian paraenesis in its Graeco-Roman and Hellenistic Jewish contexts in the light of one hundred years of scholarship, issuing from a research project by Nordic and international scholars. The concept of paraenesis is basic to New Testament scholarship but hardly anywhere else. How is that to be explained? The concept is also, notoriously, without any agreed-upon definition and it is even contested. Can it at all be salvaged? This volume reassesses the scholarly discussion of paraenesis - both the concept and the phenomenon - since Paul Wendland and Martin Dibelius and argues for a number of ways in which it may continue to be fruitful.  aWas ist frühchristliche Paränese? Im Licht einer hundertjährigen Forschungsgeschichte bieten die 17 Beiträge eine aktuelle Diskussion frühchristlicher Paränese in ihrem griechisch-römischen und hellenistisch-jüdischen Kontext. Der Band, an dem zahlreiche internationale Gelehrte mitgewirkt haben, geht auf ein skandinavisches Forschungsprojekt zurück.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aChristian literature, EarlyxHistory and criticism. 4aAlte Kirche. 4aNeues Testament. 4aParänese. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh1 aAasgaard, Reidar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetz, Hans Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1